        "newspaperPageNumber":"32",
        "trailText":"Chairman of the Treasury select committee is right to demand answers from Bank of England over plans for Chinese banks",
        "headline":"Andrew Tyrie's questions about Chinese banks in UK must be answered in full",
        "body":"<p>Well done, Andrew Tyrie. The chairman of the Treasury select committee is right to demand answers from the Bank of England on how it has come to pass that Chinese banks, usually regarded as some of the world's most impenetrable financial institutions, may soon be allowed to operate in London under a gentle form of regulatory oversight.</p><p>The difference between a bank branch and a bank subsidiary may seem a dry distinction but, in the world of financial regulation, it is critical.</p><p>Branches of foreign-controlled banks can operate with less capital and the lead role in their oversight is taken by regulators in the home country. Banks from the European Economic Area can operate in the UK this way and the privilege is usually only extended to banks from countries, such as the US, where standards of regulation are perceived to be high and where the flow of information is smooth between the Bank of England and its local counterpart.</p><p>Subsidiaries, on the other hand, must operate to UK standards on capital and be subject to normal UK regulatory scrutiny. In the post-crisis world, it had been assumed that the Bank wished to see fewer branches and more subsidiaries. That way the UK financial system ought to be safer, other factors being equal.</p><p>But George Osborne has now said that Chinese banks will be allowed to apply to open branches in the UK. These would be wholesale branches, rather than retail branches taking deposits and savings from the public. Even so, this looks like a huge shift in UK regulatory policy that had not been aired until the chancellor unveiled the news to his (presumably delighted) hosts in China this week.</p><p>Tyrie wants to know whether the Threadneedle Street's Prudential Regulation Authority (PRA) was leant upon; whether it is happy with the arrangements described by Osborne; whether the PRA's policy on branches and subsidiaries has indeed changed; and whether any changes apply only to China.</p><p>These questions are urgent. The government's current love-in with Beijing will look a dismal policy if the UK is actually whipping up business by giving special treatment to China's state-owned banks special treatment. Yes, it would be jolly nice for the City to be able to trade renminbis to its heart's content â€“ but not if the cost is a watering down of regulatory reforms and the Bank's authority. Tyrie's questions require point-by-point answers.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/420183615|2013-11-05T11:03:48Z|4ce3c6e0142ce93409f185d77cead08dd95045c5 -->",
